    "summary": "Ghana became the first sub-Saharan African country to achieve independence from European colonial rule when the former Gold Coast became the Republic of Ghana on March 6, 1957. The independence movement was led by Kwame Nkrumah, who had organized mass political action through his Convention People's Party from the late 1940s. Nkrumah had been imprisoned by the British, but his party's success in elections while he was jailed forced the colonial authorities to release him and negotiate the transition to independence.\n\nGhana's independence was a landmark event in African history and the broader process of [[event:114|decolonization]]. Nkrumah articulated a pan-African vision in which Ghana's liberation was meaningful only in the context of the liberation of all Africa. His rhetoric and the model of peaceful mass political mobilization influenced independence movements across the continent. However, Nkrumah's government grew increasingly authoritarian, and he was overthrown in a military coup in 1966 while visiting Hanoi. Ghana's post-independence history of military coups and political instability reflected broader challenges facing newly independent African states in building stable democratic institutions.",
